To begin with, we note that the columns of \emph{A} are already
orthogonal,

\begin{align*}
\begin{bmatrix}
0 & 1 & 0 & -1 & 0
\end{bmatrix} \cdot \begin{bmatrix}
1 \\ 0 \\ -1 \\ 0 \\ 1
\end{bmatrix} = 0
\end{align*}

So we can simply put the normalized columns of \emph{A} into the matrix
\emph{Q}:

\begin{align*}
Q = \begin{bmatrix}
0 & \frac1{\sqrt 3} \\
\frac1{\sqrt 2} & 0 \\
0 & -\frac1{\sqrt 3} \\
-\frac1{\sqrt 2} & 0 \\
0 & \frac1{\sqrt 3}
\end{bmatrix}
\end{align*}

As a last step, we calculate \emph{R = Q\textsuperscript{T}A} to find

\begin{align*}
R = \begin{bmatrix}
\sqrt 2 & 0 \\ 0 & \sqrt 3
\end{bmatrix}
\end{align*}

